  "answer": "**No work in the Falsafa corpus contains this specific analogy.** \n\nExtensive searches across the English translations for key phrases and concepts—\"hunter wounded deer blood thicket,\" \"wounded deer\" blood, \"trail of blood\" hunter, \"judge hunter deer blood,\" \"hunter\" deer blood, \"deer\" blood trail, hunter track deer, \"blood\" \"deer,\" hunter, deer, \"blood\" trail, judge track truth, \"circumstantial\" judge, and \"judge\" hunter—yielded no matching passages.[^1]\n\nWhile the corpus includes legal texts like *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, *Kātyāyana Smṛti*, and *Manusmṛti* that mention judges, truth-finding, circumstantial witnesses (e.g., hunters as forest-dwellers), and poetic metaphors of hunters/deer in works like *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, none describe a judge tracking truth via a wounded deer's blood trail in a thicket.\n\n[^1]: Searches conducted via `search_corpus` tool on English variant bodies; full results reviewed for relevance. Corpus limited to 38 works; not exhaustive of all philosophy.",
